      "writtenOn": "2021-02-27T22:14:53Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Can the std::vector\u003cunsigned char\u003e-based method be used instead as long as the vector is preallocated?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 284,
        "startChar": 16,
        "endLine": 284,
        "endChar": 29
      },
      "revId": "82c99f4c579e950d388aece2c6726039d85f4972",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "84b6b779_033e5cce",
        "filename": "android/android-emugl/host/include/OpenglRender/Renderer.h",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 284,
      "author": {
        "id": 1125918
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-03-01T17:44:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Technically this is possible with a custom allocator that points to our pre-allocated memory region. (There is no other way of doing this with std::vector). This would be rather risky since our allocator would technically not really allocate or de-allocate memory (it is not conform to the specification). \n\nThis can cause issues when calling resize. Now the user of this type of vector must be aware of these restrictions, which are not expressed in the type of std::vector.\n\nThis confusion does not exist with the raw pointer, where memory ownership is clear and we do not have to make any assumptions about the behavior and usage of std::vector.",
      "parentUuid": "d8be2731_c84ce8b7",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 284,
        "startChar": 16,
        "endLine": 284,
        "endChar": 29
      },
      "revId": "82c99f4c579e950d388aece2c6726039d85f4972",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9f906aef_3daea033",
        "filename": "android/android-emugl/host/include/OpenglRender/Renderer.h",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 284,
      "author": {
        "id": 1152904
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-03-01T17:53:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Why can\u0027t the vector be allocated normally but reused between screenshots?",
      "parentUuid": "84b6b779_033e5cce",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 284,
        "startChar": 16,
        "endLine": 284,
        "endChar": 29
      },
      "revId": "82c99f4c579e950d388aece2c6726039d85f4972",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "16a7f12d_e131b286",
        "filename": "android/android-emugl/host/include/OpenglRender/Renderer.h",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 284,
      "author": {
        "id": 1125918
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-03-01T18:47:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It could, but we still have to choose between:\n\n- additional memcpy\n- break std::allocate contract\n\nWe support 2 transport mechanisms:\n\n- For mmap: We have a memory region where the bytes need to end up in.\n- For gRPC: A protobuf message exposes a bytes object as std::string which the message itself owns. We are free to pre-allocate our own and inject it. Since C++17 std::string gives access to the underlying char*, it is no longer const and is guaranteed to be a contiguous memory region of the size of the string.\n\nSo for both of our transport mechanisms we can create and have access to the raw memory of the desired size.\n\nstd::vector is designed such that it owns its own internal data structures. We can only provide an allocator to provide/release memory as needed. If we go with a std::vector our options are:\n\n- Either the std::vector is created and backed by the existing memory region, which means providing our own std::allocate implementation and hope that the vector calls it in the right way.\n- Copy the final bytes in std::vector into the destination memory region.",
      "parentUuid": "9f906aef_3daea033",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 284,
        "startChar": 16,
        "endLine": 284,
        "endChar": 29
      },
